Yes, the previous version in which this bug was not present was 8.0

### Description

What's the right way to add 'fake' local certificate or just run app locally (browser and server) with https? In previous version (8.0) it was possible to add certificate to express in server.ts:

```
export const createServerForEnv = () => {
  if (process.env.ENVIRONMENT === 'dev') {
    return createHttpsServer({
      key: fs.readFileSync(path.resolve(__dirname, '../../../src/ssl/localhost.key')),
      cert: fs.readFileSync(path.resolve(__dirname, '../../../src/ssl/localhost.crt'))
    }, (req, res) => {
      requestListener(req, res);
    })
  } else {
    return createServer((req, res) => {
      requestListener(req, res);
    });
  }
}

// Start up the Node server
const server = createServerForEnv();

server.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server listening...`);
});
```

Now it's not possible to run app (browser and server) locally with https using `ng run app:serve-ssr` script.

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

Reproduction is not needed, I just want to know what's the correct way to do this in Angular Universal 9.

